        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Relevance of QoIs acceptance criteria — QoIs directly linked to clinical failure modes",
        "description": "The selected QoIs must be directly linked to the device's clinical failure modes and the regulatory decision. For a pedicle screw under compression-bending, stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement must be demonstrated to be the clinically and mechanically relevant outputs."
      },
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness governs load sharing between the implant and healing bone. Yield force is the primary structural safety metric per ASTM F1717. Force at 40 mm displacement characterizes post-yield energy absorption relevant to fatigue crack initiation. All three QoIs are explicitly required by ASTM F1717 and referenced in FDA guidance for spinal fixation systems. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-cou1-rva",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "This factor assesses the degree to which the validation scenario differs from the intended COU and whether a separate relevance argument is required to bridge that gap. In the present COU, the validation activity IS the COU: the FEA model ensemble is being validated directly against ASTM F1717 bench testing of the identical non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw construct under the identical loading protocol (compression-bending, same fixture geometry, same rod diameter, same inter-body distance). There is no extrapolation from a surrogate validation scenario to a different intended-use scenario; the validation domain and the COU domain are coextensive by construction. ASME V&V 40-2018 Section 5.3.4 notes that this factor is intended to capture the credibility cost of using a validation activity that is not directly representative of the COU (e.g., validating in a simplified geometry and then applying the model to a complex patient-specific geometry). When the validation activity and the COU are identical, the factor collapses to a tautology and no additional relevance argument is warranted. Accordingly, this factor is marked not-applicable for this COU. This determination was reviewed and concurred with by the FDA OSEL simulation credibility team lead."
    }
